ğŸ“– The Story of Fibonacci

Goal:
Find the nth Fibonacci number.
The Fibonacci sequence looks like:
0, 1, 1, 2, 3, 5, 8, 13, ...
Each number is the sum of the two before it.

Mathematically:
fib(n) = fib(n-1) + fib(n-2)

ğŸ§© The Three Parts of the Recursion Story

1ï¸âƒ£ Base Case (The Ending)
When the story is so small that the answer is already known:
if n == 0 â†’ return 0  
if n == 1 â†’ return 1

2ï¸âƒ£ Recursive Step (The Chapter Progression)
For any n > 1,
â€œIâ€™ll trust recursion to give me fib(n-1) and fib(n-2),
then Iâ€™ll just add them together.â€
return fib(n-1) + fib(n-2);

3ï¸âƒ£ Leap of Faith (The Trust)
We donâ€™t manually calculate smaller Fibonacci numbers â€”
we trust recursion to handle them and give the right answers.

âš™ï¸ Complexity
Time Complexity: O(2â¿) â†’ because each call makes two more calls.
Space Complexity: O(n) â†’ due to the recursive call stack.

int fib(int n) {
    if (n == 0 || n == 1)
        return n;           // base case
    return fib(n-1) + fib(n-2);  // recursive step
}
